# Flutter Project Conventions

## Architecture
- Use **feature-first** folder structure: `lib/features/<feature>/presentation/`, `data/`, `domain/`
- State management: **Riverpod 3.3.x** (use `@riverpod` code generation, `AsyncNotifier` for async state)
- Do NOT suggest `riverpod_lint` or `custom_lint` — incompatible with current `freezed_annotation ^3.x` + `flutter_riverpod >=3.2.1`
- Separate UI from business logic — no Firebase/API calls inside widgets

## Folder Structure
```
lib/
  features/
    booking/
      data/         # repositories, data sources, models
      domain/       # entities, use cases, repository interfaces
      presentation/ # screens, widgets, providers
  shared/
    widgets/        # reusable UI components
    theme/
    utils/
```

## Widget Rules
- Prefer `StatelessWidget` + Riverpod over `StatefulWidget`
- Always use `const` constructors where possible
- Split large widgets into smaller private widgets or separate files

## Navigation
- Use **go_router** for declarative routing — only when screens have a real back stack (e.g. calendar → booking detail)
- For simple **state-driven UI swaps** with no back stack (e.g. loading → setup → main), use a `switch` on a named enum inside the widget — do NOT add go_router just for this

```dart
// ✅ State-driven swap — no router needed
enum _ScreenState { loading, setup, calendar }

switch (_screenState) {
  _ScreenState.loading  => const CircularProgressIndicator(),
  _ScreenState.setup    => const SetupForm(),
  _ScreenState.calendar => const BookingCalendar(),
}

// ✅ Use go_router when navigation history matters
// e.g. tapping a day → booking detail screen (back button expected)
```

## Error Handling
- Never swallow errors silently
- Expose loading/error/data states via `AsyncValue` from Riverpod
